<CENTER>


<center>
<table border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" width="95%">
<tr bgcolor="#ffffff"><td>	 
<table border="0" width="100%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0">

<TR bgcolor="#000080">
<TD colspan="2" align="left">
<FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#ffffff" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<b>T O P I C     R E V I E W</b>
</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR bgcolor="#DEDFDF">
<TD valign=top>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Cheese Eater of Doom
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I am still a low druid, but even at my level, it seems snare gets resisted a lot.  I know to kite, you must use snare, but how do you do it at higher levels when I'm assuming it is resisted even more.  The MOB agros you whether it's resisted or not, and it seems like the few seconds it takes to recast snare again, you could be seriously hurt (not to mention stunned constantly).<P>So, how do you deal with it at higher levels, or does it not cost too many problems?<P>Thanks.</FONT>
</TD></TR>

<TR bgcolor="#F7F7F7">
<TD valign=top>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Gurk
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Here is how you snare at any level. First you try at max casting range. If resisted then you run away from the mob till you can cast again. Wait a good second so you make a complete stop(so you dont get interputed) then cast. If second try gets resisted, start running again as before. SoW helps a LOT when trying to snare a npc that resists a lot. If you dont have sow there is a way to out run a mob and gain enough distance to cast, but its not always worth the time. Since you can only go about 5-10% faster that way, it takes a while to gain distance, it might be best to try and chain cast till you land it.</FONT>
</TD></TR>

<TR bgcolor="#DEDFDF">
<TD valign=top>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
&lt;Ganas&gt;
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Snare at oh say lvl 40ish only gets resisted like 1/50 times, when it does it hurts lol(guys hit for nearly 100 >.<) I always have Spirt of Cheeta up, cast that, and just cast snare, if its not up I just run for a bit, generally till snare regens, then try to snare, run a bit more, snare, ect =) if down low I'll go to zone )<P>Having sow on is a must, of corse, if not consider yourself dead =) Or lucky<P>Yeah, like he said, cast at max range, you should be able to get a second snare off if you run a bit(just till snare regens on your bar) Have wolfy up if you can, tis a bit faster =) like 5% I think<P><BR>Ganas-50th Druid-Seventh Hammer-Eastern Faith</FONT>
</TD></TR>

<TR bgcolor="#F7F7F7">
<TD valign=top>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
&lt;Kamile&gt;
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">To add to Gurk's post:<P>I've found it very difficult to make my character be completely still after running (when kiting or fleeing).  He said wait a second, but I still got interrupted a lot when I tried that.  So I found that when you stop, if you turn slightly, then cast the spell, you are much less likely to be interrupted.<P>But snare is not resisted much unless you are trying to snare red things (generally speaking).  Don't get discouraged.   <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"></FONT>
</TD></TR>

<TR bgcolor="#DEDFDF">
<TD valign=top>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Trynawr Litefoot
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">to deal with the problem of being interrupted by not fully stoping i do 2 things:<BR>1)press back to stop, you stop alot quicker that way, this alone works many times.<BR>2)as Kamile said, turn slightly<BR>doing both of these i almost never get interrupted because i'm not stoped</FONT>
</TD></TR>

<TR bgcolor="#F7F7F7">
<TD valign=top>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Wolfkind
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">At 29th level you get ensnare which helps a great deal, also your sow gets faster as you level, this allows you many tries if the first fails, also helpful is the fact that the casting cost is low, and if all else fails you can stand there and keep casting it while the mob is hitting you - your channeling will help keep you from being interupted.   The nice thing about being a druid is that if you have a terrible run of bad luck bugging out is easy.<P>   I use the turn method mentioned earlier to avoid interupting my casts btw.</FONT>
</TD></TR>

<TR bgcolor="#DEDFDF">
<TD valign=top>
